# Rule 4 — Documentation

**Whenever architecture changes, documentation updates are mandatory — not optional.**

```text
Architecture change (code / SPEC / boundaries)
        ↓
Update docs
        ↓
Update ADR if needed
        ↓
Update package README
        ↓
(SPEC status / roadmap if truth changed)
```

Do this **in the same change set** as the code. Do not leave docs for “later.”

## When this rule fires

Any of:

- New/removed package boundary or dependency edge  
- New public contract, module spine, or Must not  
- Bootstrap / layering / WP integration behavior change  
- Breaking or deprecating a public API  
- Security, persistence, or extension-point design change  

If you only rename privately with zero external behavior → light touch (PHPDoc / changelog note) is enough.

## 1. Update docs

Touch the relevant sources of truth:

| Change type | Update |
| ----------- | ------ |
| Package behavior / spine | `packages/<name>/SPEC.md` |
| Cross-cutting design | `ARCHITECTURE.md` and/or `docs/architecture/*` |
| Roadmap / train | `ROADMAP.md`, `docs/roadmap/*` |
| How-to / guides | matching `docs/**` section |
| Release notes | `CHANGELOG.md` when user is cutting a version |

SPEC remains the **implementation contract**. Keep Responsibilities / Must not / Dependency Rules accurate.

## 2. Update ADR if needed

Create or amend under `docs/adr/` when the change is a **decision** (not a routine feature):

- New architectural choice or rejected alternative  
- Contradicts an Accepted ADR → new ADR (don’t silently overwrite history)  
- WP-first, package boundaries, storage, API style, security model, etc.

ADR not required for tiny bugfixes that don’t change design.

## 3. Update package README

For every package you touched architecturally:

- `packages/<name>/README.md` — purpose, spine blurb, status, how to test  
- Keep it short; deep detail stays in SPEC  

If multiple packages’ public story changed → update each affected README.

## Also update (when truth changed)

- `packages/BLUEPRINTS.md` status row  
- `.cursor/context/project.md` / `roadmap.md` if map or train shifted  
- Phase prompt in `.ai/prompts/` only if phase scope itself changed  

## Read order (before code)

1. Package `SPEC.md` + `README.md`  
2. `ARCHITECTURE.md` + `docs/adr/`  
3. `.cursor/context/project.md` + `roadmap.md`  
4. Related `docs/`  

Unclear docs → **stop and ask**. Never guess architecture.

## Anti-patterns

- ❌ Ship code that changes boundaries without SPEC/README updates  
- ❌ “Docs in a follow-up PR” for architecture changes  
- ❌ Quietly contradicting an Accepted ADR  
- ❌ Inventing unsolicited guide pages unrelated to the change  

**No architecture change is done until docs + ADR (if needed) + package README match the code.**
